                <p>I thank Professor Sanches from the bottom of my heart for the detailed analysis of our publication. I appreciate and agree with all her statements and suggestions. I have now&#x00a0;a great desire to propose a toast: "To diphtheria!". This sounds paradoxical at first glance. But there is nothing paradoxical in this. First, you should be very respectful of this infection. As rightly pointed out by Prof. Sanches, it has been killing and crippling people for centuries, so a frivolous attitude towards the disease is unacceptable. This is not a "forgotten" disease - last year diphtheria reached and spread across Europe, hiding in it. You should treat this Lady with reverence and pay attention to her constantly, and not from case to case. Western medicine often sins last: "It doesn't touch us, so let's leave everything as it is, we need money for more important matters - Covid, AIDS, hepatitis, tuberculosis&#x2026;". Or: "Vaccinate everyone and you will all be happy, no matter what you instill and how effective this vaccine is - it now works and that's the question". No, you can't do that with diphtheria. It is a cyclic disease and it will always find a GAP and avenge the disrespectful attitude towards it! For example, it would seem, for no apparent reason, diphtheria became a ZOONOSIS and began to be actively spread by animals, including pets - cats and dogs. Its diphtheria toxin has undergone many changes, and whether diphtheria vaccination will be able to form reliable protection against "ulceraphtheria" or not is a big question that has risen in our queue for study. When the situation with diphtheria aggravates, as Prof. Gladysheva, all those who previously dealt with other infections, by magic, change their orientation, rushing to save the world from diphtheria, and pseudoscientific theories appear like mushrooms after the rain, that put sticks in the wheels of real specialists. Therefore, everything must be done on time. As my great-grandfather, a Russian Professor of Medicine Dr. Makarov, from whom our medical dynasty began, and who was shot by Stalin's thugs in 1937 as a "Japanese spy" (for operating on a Japanese consul) used to say: "One gram of prevention is better than a kilogram of therapy". And the second. Diphtheria gathered at one table caring people, researchers, excellent professionally and personally, who support each other with an open soul and kind heart, but at the same time do not compromise their principles: "Plato is my friend, but the truth is dearer!". Thanks again Prof. Sanches for her selfless service to science, and, in her person, for the Brazilian School of Microbiology, rich in traditions and achievements, widely known and respected in the world.</p>
